# Security standards

CodeSage is self-hosted and handles private source code + repo tokens. Security is not optional.

## Secrets & tokens
- **Never commit secrets.** Document variables in `.env.example`; real `.env` is git/cursor-ignored.
- Repo tokens are **encrypted at rest** (app-level envelope encryption) in PostgreSQL; decrypt
  only in memory when needed (e.g. worker `sync`).
- Recommend/expect **least-privilege, read-only** deploy tokens for connected repositories.
- **Never log** secrets, tokens, passwords, or full sensitive request bodies.

## Access control
- Enforce **RBAC** (admin / expert / developer / end_user) at the API and data boundaries;
  scope queries by project. **Audit-log** sensitive actions (actor, action, target, ts).
- **Parameterized queries only**; sanitize/validate all inputs (see `database-standards.mdc`).

## Deployment posture
- **Self-hosted only:** code, embeddings, and LLM inference run on internal machines — **no
  source code leaves the network**.
- **Open-source only (NFR-10):** do not introduce paid/commercial-only products or services.
  If a capability seems to need one, raise it (write an ADR) instead of adding it.
